  <row Id="6363" PostTypeId="1" AcceptedAnswerId="6371" CreationDate="2011-10-04T16:25:45.460" Score="11" ViewCount="2119" Body="&lt;p&gt;Several general questions have been asked regarding how long a bike or bike frame will &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://bicycles.stackexchange.com/q/5409/1683&quot;&gt;last&lt;/a&gt;&quot;, and the gist of answers seems to be that a bike can last quite a while of the replaceable components are replaced and the bike is reasonably well maintained.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;But what about the inherent structural integrity of the frame itself? Is there such a thing as a risk of sudden frame failure or disintegration after some level of use? Do bikes ever fall apart, or develop a risk of breaking or fracturing along weak points? One of my bikes has more miles on it than the car I'm turning in  and I wonder about the integrity of the &lt;em&gt;car&lt;/em&gt;! &lt;/p&gt;&#xA;" OwnerUserId="1683" LastActivityDate="2013-08-02T03:22:19.347" Title="Is there such a thing as frame failure?" Tags="&lt;maintenance&gt;&lt;safety&gt;&lt;frames&gt;" AnswerCount="7" FavoriteCount="1" />
