  <row Id="7722" PostTypeId="1" CreationDate="2012-01-17T18:15:22.507" Score="8" ViewCount="1109" Body="&lt;h1&gt;Fat or Skinny?&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I think the arguments are as follows: &lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Fat: You can float on top of the snow and you don-t have to go through it.  You have a larger contact patch with the ground.  &lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Skinny: Will find it's way through the snow to find some pavement to grab onto.  &lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Studded: Works great on ice but has no effect on snow/slush/other stuff.  (Note never tried studded tires so just speculating).&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1&gt;Conditions of Interest&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I am interested in traction on: &lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Cleared city streets&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Uncleared city streets&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i.stack.imgur.com/37rDj.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;enter image description here&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Uncleared city streets where cars have gone through and made deep ruts&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i.stack.imgur.com/8BuQ3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;enter image description here&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Slush&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i.stack.imgur.com/N7Y2s.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;enter image description here&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Slush that has re-frozen into deep ruts&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Ice patches&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note: All pictures are take from google images.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1&gt;Background&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I have a short commute through part of Ottawa and run lots of erands on my bike.  When it is snowing and when the roads don't look good I have several routes that are only slow residential streets so 